🚗 𝐏𝐈𝐃 𝐋𝐢𝐧𝐞 𝐅𝐨𝐥𝐥𝐨𝐰𝐞𝐫 𝐑𝐨𝐛𝐨𝐭 (𝐐𝐓𝐑-𝟏𝟔 + 𝐓𝐞𝐞𝐧𝐬𝐲 𝟒.𝟏)

This project implements a high-speed PID-controlled line follower robot using a 16-element Pololu QTR analog sensor array, powered by the Teensy 4.1 microcontroller and driven by a TB6612 motor driver.

The goal of this project is to achieve precise line tracking, smooth motion, and fast response using a well-tuned PID control system.

📌 𝑭𝒆𝒂𝒕𝒖𝒓𝒆𝒔:
  🔍 16-sensor line detection for high-resolution tracking
  ⚡ Fast control loop using Teensy 4.1
  🎯 PID-based correction (Kp, Kd) for accurate steering
  🔄 Customizable motor control via TB6612 driver
  🧠 Easily adaptable to other microcontrollers
⚙️ 𝑯𝒂𝒓𝒅𝒘𝒂𝒓𝒆 𝑼𝒔𝒆𝒅:
  🧩 Microcontroller: Teensy 4.1
  📡 Sensor Array: Pololu QTR-16 Analog Sensor Array
  🔌 Motor Driver: TB6612FNG Motor Driver
  ⚙️ DC Motors with gearbox
  🔋 Battery pack

🧠 𝑯𝒐𝒘 𝑰𝒕 𝑾𝒐𝒓𝒌𝒔

The robot uses the QTR sensor array to detect the position of the line. Based on this position, an error value is calculated.

The PID controller computes correction using:

Proportional (Kp) → reacts to current error
Derivative (Kd) → reacts to the rate of change of error

This correction is applied to motor speeds to keep the robot aligned with the line.

🔧 𝐂𝐨𝐝𝐞 𝐂𝐮𝐬𝐭𝐨𝐦𝐢𝐳𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧

You can easily adapt this code to your setup:

1. Sensor Pins

Modify the sensors[] array in the code:

int sensors[] = {A0, A1, A2, ..., A15};

➡️ Ensure all pins are connected to ADC-capable pins on your microcontroller.

2. PID Tuning

Adjust these parameters for best performance:

float Kp = 0.8;
float Kd = 4.5;
Increase Kp → faster response, but may oscillate
Increase Kd → smoother motion, reduces overshoot
3. Motor Driver Pins

Update motor control pins according to your wiring:

#define AIN1 2
#define AIN2 3
#define PWMA 4
#define BIN1 5
#define BIN2 6
#define PWMB 7
⚠️ Important Notes
✅ QTR analog sensor pins must be connected to ADC pins
⚡ Ensure proper power supply for motors and controller
🔧 Perform sensor calibration before running the bot
🧪 PID tuning is critical for optimal performance
